| seats1_title = [[Senate (Burundi)|Senate]] | seats1 = {{Composition bar|0|49|hex=#000099}} | seats2_title = [[Burundian legislative election, 2010|National Assembly]] | seats2 = {{Composition bar|0|106|hex=#000099}} }}
The '''National Council for the Defense of Democracy''' ({{Lang-fr|Conseil National Pour la Défense de la Démocratie}}, CNDD) is a political party in [[Burundi]].
==History== The CNDD was established in [[Democratic Republic of the Congo|Zaire]] on 24 September 1994 and was initially led by [[Léonard Nyangoma]].<ref>Tom Lansford (2014) ''Political Handbook of the World 2014 '', CQ Press, p211</ref><ref name=PH/> The party also established an armed wing, the [[Forces for the Defence of Democracy]], which was involved in the country's ethnic conflict. In the early 2000s the party split, with a faction led by [[Pierre Nkurunziza]] becoming the [[National Council for the Defense of Democracy – Forces for the Defense of Democracy]] (CNDD–FDD). The CNDD held two ministerial posts in a unity government formed in 2001.<ref name=PH>[http://www.cndd-burundi.com/le-parti/histoire-parti Party history] CNDD {{fr icon}}</ref>
In the [[Burundian legislative election, 2005|2005 parliamentary elections]] on 4 July the party received 4% of the vote, winning four of the 118 seats in the [[National Assembly (Burundi)|National Assembly]], whilst the CNDD–FDD won 64.<ref>[http://africanelections.tripod.com/bi.html#2005_National_Assembly_Election Elections in Burundi] Elections in Africa</ref> It had performed strongly in local elections in June in [[Bururi Province|Bururi]], Nyangoma's home province,<ref name=TL2>Lansford, p214</ref> receiving 4.2% of the national vote and winning 135 of the 3,225 local council seats across the country.<ref>[http://www.content.eisa.org.za/sites/eisa.org.za/files/imports/import-data/WEP/bur2005local.htm Burundi: 2005 Communal election results] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140105101810/http://www.content.eisa.org.za/sites/eisa.org.za/files/imports/import-data/WEP/bur2005local.htm |date=2014-01-05 }} EISA</ref> It subsequently won a single seat in the indirect Senate elections on 29 July, which was elected by colleges of local councillors,<ref>[http://www.ipu.org/parline-e/reports/arc/2368_05.htm Burundi Sénat (Senate): Elections held in 2005] IPU</ref> and gained an additional two co-opted seats.<ref>[http://africanelections.tripod.com/indirect.html Indirect Legislative Elections in Sub-Saharan Africa] African Elections Database</ref> However, Nyangoma went into exile the following year, before returning in 2007.
On 1 June 2010 the party was one of several that withdrew from the [[Burundian presidential election, 2010|presidential elections]] scheduled for 28 June, accusing the Independent National Elections Commission of incompetence and a lack of impartiality.<ref name=ICG>[http://www.crisisgroup.org/~/media/Files/africa/central-africa/burundi/169%20Burundi%20-%20From%20Electoral%20Boycott%20to%20Political%20Impasse%20ENGLISH.pdf Burundi: From electoral boycott to political impasse] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140626161226/http://www.crisisgroup.org/~/media/Files/africa/central-africa/burundi/169%20Burundi%20-%20From%20Electoral%20Boycott%20to%20Political%20Impasse%20ENGLISH.pdf |date=2014-06-26 }} International Crisis Group</ref> Following the elections, Nyangoma went into exile again, fearing that his parliamentary immunity would be lifted.<ref name=ICG/> The CNDD did not participate in the [[Burundian legislative election, 2010|parliamentary elections]] on 23 July 2010.<ref>[http://www.ipu.org/parline-e/reports/2049_E.htm Burundi Inama Nshingamateka (National Assembly): Elections held in 2010] IPU</ref>
